[3.9 Modification of the Database]
	(3.9.1 Deletion)
		- we can delete only "whole" tuples
			ex)
				DELETE FROM relation
				WHERE Predicate;

			* WHERE clause can be omitted.

		- we MUST use one "DELETE" command for each relation.

		- can contain a nested "SELECT" that references the relation from which tuples are to be deleted.
			ex)
				DELETE FROM instructor
				WHERE salary < (SELECT AVG(salary)
								FROM instructor);

	(3.9.2 Insertion)
		- simplest "INSERT" statement
			-> request to insert one tuple
				ex)
					INSERT INTO course
					VALUES ('CS-437', 'DB Systems', 'Comp. Sci', 4);

	(3.9.3 Updates)
		ex)
			UPDATE instructor
			SET salary = salary * 1.05;

			UPDATE instructor
			SET salary = salary * 1.05
			WHERE salary < 70000;

		- general form of the case statement
			ex)
				CASE
					WHEN pred1 then result1
					WHEN pred2 then result2
					...
					WHEN predn then resultn
					ELSE result0
				end

				UPDATE instructor
				SET salary = CASE
								WHEN salary <= 10000 THEN salary*1.05
								ELSE salary*1.03
							 END

		- Many systems support a "COALESCE" function
			-> concise way of replacing "nulls" by other values.

			ex) COALESCE(SUM(credits), 0) instead of CASE expression.